          "author": 1,
          "author_avatar_urls": {
            "24": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/fa4469e1482fe3b86eacc2d2535c921931822199af987ac0e7003dca5d78a196?s=24&r=g",
            "48": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/fa4469e1482fe3b86eacc2d2535c921931822199af987ac0e7003dca5d78a196?s=48&r=g",
            "96": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/fa4469e1482fe3b86eacc2d2535c921931822199af987ac0e7003dca5d78a196?s=96&r=g"
          },
          "author_name": "Daryll Swer",
          "author_url": "http://daryllswer.com/",
          "content": {
            "rendered": "<p>Hi</p>\n<p>The prefix list by default seems to be an exact match already, even though Juniper doesn&#8217;t explicitly say it <a href=\"https://www.juniper.net/documentation/us/en/software/junos/routing-policy/topics/ref/statement/prefix-list-edit-policy-options.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">here</a>.</p>\n<p>We&#8217;ve been using prefix list on many other routers in different ASes with no problems for exporting only aggregates.</p>\n<p>Another user also tested the config and <a href=\"https://github.com/topranks/homerlabs/tree/main/labs/filterlab\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">confirmed</a>, there&#8217;s nothing wrong with using prefix list directly as I did.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s also based on the simple logical fact that if a reboot fixed the issue, then the issue isn&#8217;t in the config. If it was the config, then why would a reboot fix the issue?</p>\n"
          },
          "date": "2023-03-29T12:02:51",
          "id": 127,
          "link": "https://www.daryllswer.com/navigating-a-bgp-zombie-outbreak-on-juniper-routers/#comment-127",
          "parent": 126,
          "type": "comment"
        },
        {
